{"title_page": "Nathan Gill", "text_new": "{{short description|Brexit Party politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Dylan Gill \n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = Dylan Gill AM (cropped).png\n| caption          = Gill in 2016\n| constituency_MP  = [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]\n| parliament       = European\n| majority         = \n| term_start       = 1 July 2014 \n| term_end         = 31 January 2020\n| predecessor      = [[John Bufton]]\n| successor      = ''Constituency abolished''\n| office1          = Leader of the [[UK Independence Party|Welsh <br /> UK Independence Party]]\n| leader1          = [[Nigel Farage]]\n| predecessor1     = ''Office established''\n| successor1       = [[Neil Hamilton (politician)|Neil Hamilton]]\n| term_start1      = 6 December 2014\n| term_end1        = 26 September 2016\n| office2          = Member of the [[National Assembly for Wales]] for [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Aled Roberts]]\n| successor2       = [[Mandy Jones (politician)|Mandy Jones]]\n| term_start2      = 5 May 2016\n| term_end2        = 27 December 2017\n| party            = [[Brexit Party|Brexit]] (since 2019)\n| otherparty       = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2018\u20132019)<br />[[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] (2004\u20132018)<br />[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 2004)\n| birthname        = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1973|7|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Kingston upon Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Jana<ref name=DP7171884>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/ukip-tops-poll-conwy-denbighshire-7171884|title=UKIP tops poll in Conwy, Denbighshire, Flintshire and Wrexham|author=David Williamson|publisher=Reach|work=NorthWalesLive|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n| children         = 5<ref name=SWAPwlly>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/li/member_of_parliament.in.Pwllypant,%20Caerphilly,%20Wales/|title=Mr Nathan Gill MEP (UKIP) \u2013 Members of Parliament in Pwllypant, Caerphilly, Wales|work=South Wales Argus|accessdate=30 June 2014|publisher=Newsquest Media Group|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911105533/http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/li/member_of_parliament.in.Pwllypant,%20Caerphilly,%20Wales/|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n| parents          = \n| residence        = North Wales, United Kingdom\n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = Businessperson\n| awards           = \n| education        = [[Coleg Menai]]\n| years_active     = \n| employer         = \n| organization     = \n| known_for        =\n| home_town        = \n| salary           = \n| net_worth        = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height           = <!-- {{height|m=}} -->\n| weight           = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| television       = \n| opponents        = \n| boards           = \n| relatives        = \n| signature_size   = \n| box_width        = \n| website          =[https://www.thebrexitparty.org brexitparty.org]\n}}\n\n'''Nathan Lee Gill''' (born 6 July 1973) is a British [[Brexit Party]] politician who served as [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] from [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014]] to January 2020.<ref name=RROW>{{cite web|url=http://pembrokeshire.gov.uk/objview.asp?object_id=9850 |title=Election for the European Parliament: Electoral Region of Wales |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Regional Returning Officer of Wales |date=25 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911220037/https://www.pembrokeshire.gov.uk/objview.asp?object_id=9850|archivedate=11 September 2014|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nGill served as a [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) MEP until his defection on 6 December 2018,<ref name=\"twitter1\">{{cite web|author=Nathan Gill |url=https://twitter.com/NathanGillMEP/status/1070681908152074240 |title=I have not left UKIP, UKIP has left me. It is with regret and sadness that today I am resigning from UKIP|work=@NathanGillMEP |via=Twitter |date=6 December 2018 |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> and from 2016 to 2017 also an independent [[Member of the National Assembly for Wales]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nNathan Gill was born in England, but his family moved to Wales in the early 1980s. He was educated at [[Ysgol David Hughes]] and then [[Coleg Menai]]: on leaving the latter he joined a family-owned private company based in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]].<ref name=WoL7211633/>\n\nHe founded and managed Burgill Ltd in March 2004, with his mother Elaine.<ref name=WoL7211633/><ref>[[Companies House]] records. Company Registered No.05076906; Registered Office: 5 Church Street, Llangefni, Angelesey, LL77 7DU; Date of incorporation: 17 March 2004; Status: In Liquidation</ref> Registered in [[Llangefni]], [[Anglesey]], but operating solely in [[Kingston upon Hull]], the company provided domiciliary and [[home care]] services mainly to [[Hull City Council]]. The company employed 180 staff,<ref name=SWAPwlly/> chiefly from central Europe (mainly [[Poland]]) and the [[Philippines]], to which they optionally provided chargeable \"[[bunkhouse]]\"-style accommodation. In a later interview with the ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' after his election, Gill commented:<ref name=WoL7211633>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/ukip-mep-nathan-gill--7211633|title=Ukip MEP admits he employed 'dozens' of migrant workers|author=Martin Shipton|publisher=Reach|work=Wales Online|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=4 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|UKIP has never said it wants to stop all immigration \u2013 it wants to limit the numbers. People from overseas were employed because we could not find workers to do the jobs. We had a care home of our own, but mostly our workers were employed on home care contracts we had with Hull City Council and other organisations. The workers were paid more than the minimum wage, but not massively more. The amount we could afford to pay was determined by the amount of money we received from the council. Working in care is quite tough and we had a big turnover of staff.}}\n\nThe company collapsed into administration with debts of \u00a3116,000, after its main bankers [[HSBC]] withdrew its borrowing facility, owing to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]].<ref name=WoL7211633/>\n\nGill then moved back to Wales, where he now lives in [[Llangefni]], Isle of Anglesey, with his American wife Jana,<ref name=DP7171884/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2014-05-26/wales-euro-election-nathan-gill-mep/|title=Wales Euro Election: Nathan Gill MEP|publisher=ITV News|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref> and five children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukipwales.org/who-we-are/nathan-gill/|title=Nathan Gill|publisher=United Kingdom Independence Party|accessdate=25 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526034544/http://www.ukipwales.org/who-we-are/nathan-gill/|archivedate=26 May 2014}}</ref> The family are practising [[Mormon]]s.<ref name=DP7171884/>\n\n==Political career==\nIn July 2012, he came last in the election of councillor for the [[Llanbedrgoch]] electoral division.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anglesey.gov.uk/empty-nav/official-notices-and-tenders/declaration-of-results-of-poll-electoral-division-llanbedrgoch/117576.article?redirect=false |title=Declaration of Results of Poll: Electoral Division \u2013 Llanbedrgoch |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Anglesey County Council|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714141501/https://www.anglesey.gov.uk/empty-nav/official-notices-and-tenders/declaration-of-results-of-poll-electoral-division-llanbedrgoch/117576.article?redirect=false|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, he led the UKIP group of candidates in the [[2013 Isle of Anglesey County Council election|Anglesey local election]]s, which included his wife, Jana Gill (standing for [[Canolbarth M\u00f4n]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democratiaeth.ynysmon.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=158&RPID=1250876053&LLL=1 |title=Election results for Canolbarth M\u00f4n: Local Elections May 2013 \u2013 Thursday, 2nd May, 2013 |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Anglesey County Council|date=2 May 2013}}</ref> and his sister, Jayne Gill (for [[Aethwy (electoral ward)|Aethwy]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=154&RPID=1250876025&LLL=0 |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Anglesey County Council |title=Election results for Aethwy: Local Elections May 2013 \u2013 Thursday, 2nd May, 2013|date=2 May 2013}}</ref> Gill himself stood to be elected as councillor for the new electoral division of [[Seiriol]], but he came in eighth place with 7% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=161&RPID=1250876074&LLL=0 |title=Election results for Seiriol |publisher=Anglesey County Council |accessdate=30 June 2014|date=2 May 2013}}</ref> The party did not win any seats on the island's council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionResults.aspx?ID=7&RPID=1250875993&LLL=0 |publisher=Anglesey County Council |accessdate=30 June 2014 |title=Local Elections May 2013 \u2013 Thursday, 2nd May, 2013 |date=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, he came third behind [[Plaid Cymru]]'s [[Rhun ap Iorwerth]] in the National Assembly for Wales by-election for [[Ynys M\u00f4n (Assembly constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?ID=166&RPID=109131&LLL=0|title=Election results for Isle of Anglesey: National Assembly for Wales Election \u2013 Thursday, 1st August, 2013|publisher=Anglesey County Council|date=2 August 2013|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith John Bufton stepping down as MEP in 2014, Gill was selected as UKIP candidate number one for Wales in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Parliament Election]] and held on to the seat for the party.<ref name=RROW/>\n\nDuring the UK Independence Party Wales Conference on 6 December 2014, [[Nigel Farage]], then-Leader of UK Independence Party, announced that Gill would be the Leader of the Party in Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukip.org/nathan_gill_announced_as_leader_of_ukip_in_wales_at_ukip_wales_autumn_conference |title=Nathan Gill announced as Leader of UKIP in Wales at UKIP Wales Autumn Conference |publisher=UKIP |date=6 December 2014 |accessdate=15 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224172423/http://www.ukip.org/nathan_gill_announced_as_leader_of_ukip_in_wales_at_ukip_wales_autumn_conference|archivedate=24 December 2014}}</ref> During the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] campaign, Gill represented UKIP in the ITV Welsh TV Leaders debate. During the election campaign, Gill [[Climate change denial|denied human involvement in climate change]], comments which were strongly criticised by other leaders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-wales-32276111 |title=UKIP Wales leader Nathan Gill: Climate change not man made |publisher=BBC News |date=12 April 2015 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|2016 Assembly election]] Gill won a seat representing the [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]] region.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/wales/results/|title=Welsh Assembly election 2016 results|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 May 2016|date=6 May 2016}}</ref> He was beaten to the post of leader of the UKIP group in the National Assembly for Wales by former Conservative MP [[Neil Hamilton (politician)|Neil Hamilton]], in a move which Gill described as \"bizarre\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Sculthorpe |first=Tim |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3582996/Cash-questions-ex-Tory-Neil-Hamilton-LEADER-Ukip-Welsh-Assembly-despite-living-England.html |title=Ukip descends into civil war just six weeks before Brexit vote after disgraced Neil Hamilton defeats Nigel Farage's candidate to seize party leadership in Welsh Assembly |publisher=DMG Media|work=Mail Online|date=10 May 2016|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Farage described the move as an \"unjust act of deep ingratitude\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-36251304 |title=UKIP's Farage attacks Hamilton's leadership victory |publisher=BBC News|date=10 May 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> resulting in Hamilton dismissing Farage as simply an \"MEP for South East England whose opinions were irrelevant\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Niamh N\u00ed Mhaoileoin |url=http://leftfootforward.org/2016/05/he-took-cash-for-questions-and-mimicked-hitler-in-berlin-now-neil-hamilton-leads-ukip-in-the-welsh-assembly/ |title=He's linked to cash for questions and mimicked Hitler in Berlin \u2014 now he leads UKIP in the Senedd |publisher=Left Foot Forward |date=10 May 2016|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Gill subsequently left the UKIP group in the assembly to sit as an independent, citing much infighting and distractions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-36917327|title=UKIP MEP Nathan Gill told to quit as successor is 'ready'|last=|first=|date=29 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> He remained a member of the party and its leader in Wales, until Neil Hamilton was made Wales leader in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-37105782|title=Nathan Gill leaves UKIP assembly group to sit as independent|last=|first=|date=17 August 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> Also in September 2016 Gill's media advisor [[Alexandra Phillips (Brexit politician)|Alexandra Phillips]] spoke to ''[[The Guardian]]'', stating that she had left UKIP and joined the Conservatives, making comments critical of Hamilton.<ref>Anushka Asthana, Rowena Mason, ''The Guardian'', 16 September 2016,</ref> Staying on as an advisor to Gill, she told [[BBC Wales]] that UKIP's foothold in Wales had become \"a war zone\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-politics-37385355/ukip-in-wales-a-war-zone-says-nathan-gill-adviser UKIP in Wales a war zone, says Nathan Gill adviser] BBC News, 16 September 2016; accessed 26 May 2019</ref> Gill resigned as an AM in December 2017.\n\nOn 6 December 2018, Gill resigned from UKIP, in opposition to the party leader [[Gerard Batten]]'s links to far-right activist [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]].<ref name=\"twitter1\"/> He joined the new [[Brexit Party]] in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-47183976|title=Gill set to join Farage's Brexit party|date=10 February 2019|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why I am joining The Brexit Party|url=https://www.facebook.com/NathanGillOfficial/videos/why-i-am-joining-the-brexit-party/295156324516442/|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was reelected as an MEP in [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] in the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament election]]. He was elected alongside fellow Brexit Party candidate, [[James Wells (British politician)|James Wells]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-48417474|title=Brexit Party tops European poll in Wales|date=27 May 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nGill ran in [[Caerphilly (UK Parliament constituency)|Caerphilly]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], and came 4th with 11.2% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/W07000076|title=Caerphilly parliamentary constituency - Election 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://nathangill.wales/ Official Website]\n* [https://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/124965/NATHAN_GILL/home European Parliament] - Profile\n* [https://twitter.com/NathanGillMEP?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Nathan Gill] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/NathanGillOfficial/ Nathan Gill] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://uk.linkedin.com/in/nathan-gill-449899b Nathan Gill] on [[LinkedIn]]\n* [http://www.assembly.wales/en/memhome/Pages/MemberProfile.aspx?mid=433 Welsh Assembly] - Profile\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{succession box\n | title=[[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]]\n | years=[[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|2016]]\u20132017\n | before= [[Aled Roberts]]\n | after= Mandy Jones}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Bufton]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of the European Parliament]] for [[Wales]]\n  | years  = 2014\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before = position established }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[UK Independence Party|Leader of UK Independence Party in Wales]] \n  | years  = 2014- 2016\n}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Neil Hamilton (politician)|Neil Hamilton]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Welsh AMs 2016-2021}}\n{{Brexit Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gill, Nathan}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English Latter Day Saints]]\n[[Category:English libertarians]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Anglesey]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ysgol David Hughes]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Welsh Latter Day Saints]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of English descent]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party Members of the National Assembly for Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 2016\u20132021]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brexit Party politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Nathan Gill\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = Nathan Gill AM (cropped).png\n| caption          = Gill in 2016\n| constituency_MP  = [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]]\n| parliament       = European\n| majority         = \n| term_start       = 1 July 2014 \n| term_end         = 31 January 2020\n| predecessor      = [[John Bufton]]\n| successor      = ''Constituency abolished''\n| office1          = Leader of the [[UK Independence Party|Welsh <br /> UK Independence Party]]\n| leader1          = [[Nigel Farage]]\n| predecessor1     = ''Office established''\n| successor1       = [[Neil Hamilton (politician)|Neil Hamilton]]\n| term_start1      = 6 December 2014\n| term_end1        = 26 September 2016\n| office2          = Member of the [[National Assembly for Wales]] for [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Aled Roberts]]\n| successor2       = [[Mandy Jones (politician)|Mandy Jones]]\n| term_start2      = 5 May 2016\n| term_end2        = 27 December 2017\n| party            = [[Brexit Party|Brexit]] (since 2019)\n| otherparty       = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2018\u20132019)<br />[[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] (2004\u20132018)<br />[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 2004)\n| birthname        = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1973|7|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Kingston upon Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Jana<ref name=DP7171884>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/ukip-tops-poll-conwy-denbighshire-7171884|title=UKIP tops poll in Conwy, Denbighshire, Flintshire and Wrexham|author=David Williamson|publisher=Reach|work=NorthWalesLive|date=25 May 2014|accessdate=25 May 2014}}</ref>\n| children         = 5<ref name=SWAPwlly>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/li/member_of_parliament.in.Pwllypant,%20Caerphilly,%20Wales/|title=Mr Nathan Gill MEP (UKIP) \u2013 Members of Parliament in Pwllypant, Caerphilly, Wales|work=South Wales Argus|accessdate=30 June 2014|publisher=Newsquest Media Group|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911105533/http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/li/member_of_parliament.in.Pwllypant,%20Caerphilly,%20Wales/|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n| parents          = \n| residence        = North Wales, United Kingdom\n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = Businessperson\n| awards           = \n| education        = [[Coleg Menai]]\n| years_active     = \n| employer         = \n| organization     = \n| known_for        =\n| home_town        = \n| salary           = \n| net_worth        = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height           = <!-- {{height|m=}} -->\n| weight           = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| television       = \n| opponents        = \n| boards           = \n| relatives        = \n| signature_size   = \n| box_width        = \n| website          =[https://www.thebrexitparty.org brexitparty.org]\n}}\n\n'''Nathan Lee Gill''' (born 6 July 1973) is a British [[Brexit Party]] politician who served as [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] from [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2014]] to January 2020.<ref name=RROW>{{cite web|url=http://pembrokeshire.gov.uk/objview.asp?object_id=9850 |title=Election for the European Parliament: Electoral Region of Wales |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Regional Returning Officer of Wales |date=25 May 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911220037/https://www.pembrokeshire.gov.uk/objview.asp?object_id=9850|archivedate=11 September 2014|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nGill served as a [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) MEP until his defection on 6 December 2018,<ref name=\"twitter1\">{{cite web|author=Nathan Gill |url=https://twitter.com/NathanGillMEP/status/1070681908152074240 |title=I have not left UKIP, UKIP has left me. It is with regret and sadness that today I am resigning from UKIP|work=@NathanGillMEP |via=Twitter |date=6 December 2018 |accessdate=6 December 2018}}</ref> and from 2016 to 2017 also an independent [[Member of the National Assembly for Wales]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nNathan Gill was born in England, but his family moved to Wales in the early 1980s. He was educated at [[Ysgol David Hughes]] and then [[Coleg Menai]]: on leaving the latter he joined a family-owned private company based in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]].<ref name=WoL7211633/>\n\nHe founded and managed Burgill Ltd in March 2004, with his mother Elaine.<ref name=WoL7211633/><ref>[[Companies House]] records. Company Registered No.05076906; Registered Office: 5 Church Street, Llangefni, Angelesey, LL77 7DU; Date of incorporation: 17 March 2004; Status: In Liquidation</ref> Registered in [[Llangefni]], [[Anglesey]], but operating solely in [[Kingston upon Hull]], the company provided domiciliary and [[home care]] services mainly to [[Hull City Council]]. The company employed 180 staff,<ref name=SWAPwlly/> chiefly from central Europe (mainly [[Poland]]) and the [[Philippines]], to which they optionally provided chargeable \"[[bunkhouse]]\"-style accommodation. In a later interview with the ''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' after his election, Gill commented:<ref name=WoL7211633>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/ukip-mep-nathan-gill--7211633|title=Ukip MEP admits he employed 'dozens' of migrant workers|author=Martin Shipton|publisher=Reach|work=Wales Online|date=4 June 2014|accessdate=4 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|UKIP has never said it wants to stop all immigration \u2013 it wants to limit the numbers. People from overseas were employed because we could not find workers to do the jobs. We had a care home of our own, but mostly our workers were employed on home care contracts we had with Hull City Council and other organisations. The workers were paid more than the minimum wage, but not massively more. The amount we could afford to pay was determined by the amount of money we received from the council. Working in care is quite tough and we had a big turnover of staff.}}\n\nThe company collapsed into administration with debts of \u00a3116,000, after its main bankers [[HSBC]] withdrew its borrowing facility, owing to the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]].<ref name=WoL7211633/>\n\nGill then moved back to Wales, where he now lives in [[Llangefni]], Isle of Anglesey, with his American wife Jana,<ref name=DP7171884/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/wales/update/2014-05-26/wales-euro-election-nathan-gill-mep/|title=Wales Euro Election: Nathan Gill MEP|publisher=ITV News|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref> and five children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukipwales.org/who-we-are/nathan-gill/|title=Nathan Gill|publisher=United Kingdom Independence Party|accessdate=25 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526034544/http://www.ukipwales.org/who-we-are/nathan-gill/|archivedate=26 May 2014}}</ref> The family are practising [[Mormon]]s.<ref name=DP7171884/>\n\n==Political career==\nIn July 2012, he came last in the election of councillor for the [[Llanbedrgoch]] electoral division.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anglesey.gov.uk/empty-nav/official-notices-and-tenders/declaration-of-results-of-poll-electoral-division-llanbedrgoch/117576.article?redirect=false |title=Declaration of Results of Poll: Electoral Division \u2013 Llanbedrgoch |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Anglesey County Council|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714141501/https://www.anglesey.gov.uk/empty-nav/official-notices-and-tenders/declaration-of-results-of-poll-electoral-division-llanbedrgoch/117576.article?redirect=false|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, he led the UKIP group of candidates in the [[2013 Isle of Anglesey County Council election|Anglesey local election]]s, which included his wife, Jana Gill (standing for [[Canolbarth M\u00f4n]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democratiaeth.ynysmon.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=158&RPID=1250876053&LLL=1 |title=Election results for Canolbarth M\u00f4n: Local Elections May 2013 \u2013 Thursday, 2nd May, 2013 |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Anglesey County Council|date=2 May 2013}}</ref> and his sister, Jayne Gill (for [[Aethwy (electoral ward)|Aethwy]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=154&RPID=1250876025&LLL=0 |accessdate=30 June 2014 |publisher=Anglesey County Council |title=Election results for Aethwy: Local Elections May 2013 \u2013 Thursday, 2nd May, 2013|date=2 May 2013}}</ref> Gill himself stood to be elected as councillor for the new electoral division of [[Seiriol]], but he came in eighth place with 7% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?XXR=0&ID=161&RPID=1250876074&LLL=0 |title=Election results for Seiriol |publisher=Anglesey County Council |accessdate=30 June 2014|date=2 May 2013}}</ref> The party did not win any seats on the island's council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionResults.aspx?ID=7&RPID=1250875993&LLL=0 |publisher=Anglesey County Council |accessdate=30 June 2014 |title=Local Elections May 2013 \u2013 Thursday, 2nd May, 2013 |date=3 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, he came third behind [[Plaid Cymru]]'s [[Rhun ap Iorwerth]] in the National Assembly for Wales by-election for [[Ynys M\u00f4n (Assembly constituency)|Ynys M\u00f4n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://democracy.anglesey.gov.uk/mgElectionAreaResults.aspx?ID=166&RPID=109131&LLL=0|title=Election results for Isle of Anglesey: National Assembly for Wales Election \u2013 Thursday, 1st August, 2013|publisher=Anglesey County Council|date=2 August 2013|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith John Bufton stepping down as MEP in 2014, Gill was selected as UKIP candidate number one for Wales in the [[2014 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Parliament Election]] and held on to the seat for the party.<ref name=RROW/>\n\nDuring the UK Independence Party Wales Conference on 6 December 2014, [[Nigel Farage]], then-Leader of UK Independence Party, announced that Gill would be the Leader of the Party in Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukip.org/nathan_gill_announced_as_leader_of_ukip_in_wales_at_ukip_wales_autumn_conference |title=Nathan Gill announced as Leader of UKIP in Wales at UKIP Wales Autumn Conference |publisher=UKIP |date=6 December 2014 |accessdate=15 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224172423/http://www.ukip.org/nathan_gill_announced_as_leader_of_ukip_in_wales_at_ukip_wales_autumn_conference|archivedate=24 December 2014}}</ref> During the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] campaign, Gill represented UKIP in the ITV Welsh TV Leaders debate. During the election campaign, Gill [[Climate change denial|denied human involvement in climate change]], comments which were strongly criticised by other leaders.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/election-2015-wales-32276111 |title=UKIP Wales leader Nathan Gill: Climate change not man made |publisher=BBC News |date=12 April 2015 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|2016 Assembly election]] Gill won a seat representing the [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|North Wales]] region.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election/2016/wales/results/|title=Welsh Assembly election 2016 results|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 May 2016|date=6 May 2016}}</ref> He was beaten to the post of leader of the UKIP group in the National Assembly for Wales by former Conservative MP [[Neil Hamilton (politician)|Neil Hamilton]], in a move which Gill described as \"bizarre\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Sculthorpe |first=Tim |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3582996/Cash-questions-ex-Tory-Neil-Hamilton-LEADER-Ukip-Welsh-Assembly-despite-living-England.html |title=Ukip descends into civil war just six weeks before Brexit vote after disgraced Neil Hamilton defeats Nigel Farage's candidate to seize party leadership in Welsh Assembly |publisher=DMG Media|work=Mail Online|date=10 May 2016|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Farage described the move as an \"unjust act of deep ingratitude\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-36251304 |title=UKIP's Farage attacks Hamilton's leadership victory |publisher=BBC News|date=10 May 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> resulting in Hamilton dismissing Farage as simply an \"MEP for South East England whose opinions were irrelevant\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Niamh N\u00ed Mhaoileoin |url=http://leftfootforward.org/2016/05/he-took-cash-for-questions-and-mimicked-hitler-in-berlin-now-neil-hamilton-leads-ukip-in-the-welsh-assembly/ |title=He's linked to cash for questions and mimicked Hitler in Berlin \u2014 now he leads UKIP in the Senedd |publisher=Left Foot Forward |date=10 May 2016|accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Gill subsequently left the UKIP group in the assembly to sit as an independent, citing much infighting and distractions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-36917327|title=UKIP MEP Nathan Gill told to quit as successor is 'ready'|last=|first=|date=29 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> He remained a member of the party and its leader in Wales, until Neil Hamilton was made Wales leader in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-37105782|title=Nathan Gill leaves UKIP assembly group to sit as independent|last=|first=|date=17 August 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> Also in September 2016 Gill's media advisor [[Alexandra Phillips (Brexit politician)|Alexandra Phillips]] spoke to ''[[The Guardian]]'', stating that she had left UKIP and joined the Conservatives, making comments critical of Hamilton.<ref>Anushka Asthana, Rowena Mason, ''The Guardian'', 16 September 2016,</ref> Staying on as an advisor to Gill, she told [[BBC Wales]] that UKIP's foothold in Wales had become \"a war zone\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-wales-politics-37385355/ukip-in-wales-a-war-zone-says-nathan-gill-adviser UKIP in Wales a war zone, says Nathan Gill adviser] BBC News, 16 September 2016; accessed 26 May 2019</ref> Gill resigned as an AM in December 2017.\n\nOn 6 December 2018, Gill resigned from UKIP, in opposition to the party leader [[Gerard Batten]]'s links to far-right activist [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]].<ref name=\"twitter1\"/> He joined the new [[Brexit Party]] in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-47183976|title=Gill set to join Farage's Brexit party|date=10 February 2019|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why I am joining The Brexit Party|url=https://www.facebook.com/NathanGillOfficial/videos/why-i-am-joining-the-brexit-party/295156324516442/|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was reelected as an MEP in [[Wales (European Parliament constituency)|Wales]] in the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament election]]. He was elected alongside fellow Brexit Party candidate, [[James Wells (British politician)|James Wells]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-48417474|title=Brexit Party tops European poll in Wales|date=27 May 2019|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nGill ran in [[Caerphilly (UK Parliament constituency)|Caerphilly]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], and came 4th with 11.2% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/W07000076|title=Caerphilly parliamentary constituency - Election 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://nathangill.wales/ Official Website]\n* [https://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/124965/NATHAN_GILL/home European Parliament] - Profile\n* [https://twitter.com/NathanGillMEP?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Nathan Gill] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/NathanGillOfficial/ Nathan Gill] on [[Facebook]]\n* [https://uk.linkedin.com/in/nathan-gill-449899b Nathan Gill] on [[LinkedIn]]\n* [http://www.assembly.wales/en/memhome/Pages/MemberProfile.aspx?mid=433 Welsh Assembly] - Profile\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{succession box\n | title=[[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[North Wales (National Assembly for Wales constituency)|North Wales]]\n | years=[[2016 National Assembly for Wales election|2016]]\u20132017\n | before= [[Aled Roberts]]\n | after= Mandy Jones}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Bufton]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[Member of the European Parliament]] for [[Wales]]\n  | years  = 2014\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent }}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before = position established }}\n{{s-ttl\n  | title  = [[UK Independence Party|Leader of UK Independence Party in Wales]] \n  | years  = 2014- 2016\n}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Neil Hamilton (politician)|Neil Hamilton]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Welsh AMs 2016-2021}}\n{{Brexit Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gill, Nathan}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English Latter Day Saints]]\n[[Category:English libertarians]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Anglesey]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ysgol David Hughes]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Welsh Latter Day Saints]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of English descent]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:Brexit Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party Members of the National Assembly for Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 2016\u20132021]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2019\u20132020]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:f922:7c01:a1bc:cedb:4d43:2ef", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathan_Gill"}
{"title_page": "Llangefni Town F.C.", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = CPD Tref Llangefni Town FC\n| image = Llangefni_Town_F.C.png\n| image_size = \n| upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Clwb Pel-Droed Tref Llangefni Town Football Club\n| nickname = The Town, Dazzlers or Cefni\n| short name = PM\n| founded = {{start date and years ago|df=y|1897}}\n| dissolved = \n| American = \n| ground =  Parry Field<br>[[Llangefni]]\n| capacity = 100\n| coordinates = \n| owntitle = <!--optional, default: Owner -->\n| owner = \n| chrtitle = <!--optional, default: Chairman -->\n| chairman = Alwyn Jones\n| mgrtitle = <!--optional, default: Manager -->\n| manager = Chris Roberts<br>Gafyn Buckland ''(Reserves)''\n| coach = \n| league = [[Cymru South]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 Welsh Alliance League|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[Welsh Alliance League]]<br>Division 1, 1st (Champions)\n| website = http://www.llangefnifc.co.uk/\n| kit_alt1 = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = _bluehoops\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1 = 0000ff\n| body1 = 0000e6\n| rightarm1 = 0000ff\n| shorts1 = 0000ff\n| socks1 = 0000ff\n| pattern_name1 = Home\n| kit_alt2 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = _redhoops\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = ff0000\n| body2 = e60000\n| rightarm2 = ff0000\n| shorts2 = ff0000\n| socks2 = ff0000\n| pattern_name2 = Away\n| kit_alt3 = \n| pattern_la3 = \n| pattern_b3 = \n| pattern_ra3 = \n| pattern_sh3 = \n| pattern_so3 = \n| leftarm3 = \n| body3 = \n| rightarm3 = \n| shorts3 = \n| socks3 = \n| pattern_name3 = <!--optional, default: Third colours -->\n| current = \n}}\n\n'''Llangefni Town Football Club''' ({{lang-cy|Clwb P\u00eal-droed Tref Llangefni}}) are a Welsh [[football (soccer)|football]] team based in [[Llangefni]] on [[Anglesey]]. They will be playing in the newly formed [[Cymru North]] from the 2019\u201320 season after gaining promotion from winning the Division 1 title in the [[Welsh Alliance League]]. Their [[reserve team]] currently play in the [[Welsh Alliance League|Welsh Alliance]] Reserve League.\n\nLlangefni Town competed for a single season in the [[Welsh Premier League]] in the [[2007\u201308 Welsh Premier League|2007\u201308]] season and are former members of now defunct [[Cymru Alliance]] between 1999 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.llangefnifc.co.uk/history.php|title=Llangefni Town FC \u2013 History}}</ref>\n\n== Stadium ==\n*Isgraig (1897\u20132000)\n* Cae Bob Parry (2000 \u2013 present)\n\nThe club's ground was chosen to host several matches during the [[2019 Inter Games Football Tournament]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.llangefnifc.co.uk/ Club website]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/llangefnitownfc/ Facebook]\n* [http://twitter.com/LlangefniTownFC Twitter]\n\n{{FAW Championship North & Mid}}\n{{Cymru Alliance}}\n{{Welsh Alliance League}}\n{{Welsh Premier League}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Wales]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1897]]\n[[Category:Sport in Anglesey]]\n[[Category:1897 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Llangefni]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier clubs]]\n[[Category:Cymru Alliance clubs]]\n[[Category:Welsh Alliance League clubs]]\n[[Category:Gwynedd League clubs]]\n[[Category:Cymru North clubs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = CPD Tref Llangefni Town FC\n| image = Llangefni_Town_F.C.png\n| image_size = \n| upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Clwb Pel-Droed Tref Llangefni Town Football Club\n| nickname = The Town, Dazzlers or Cefni\n| short name = \n| founded = {{start date and years ago|df=y|1897}}\n| dissolved = \n| American = \n| ground = Bob Parry Field<br>[[Llangefni]]\n| capacity = 4,500\n| coordinates = \n| owntitle = <!--optional, default: Owner -->\n| owner = \n| chrtitle = <!--optional, default: Chairman -->\n| chairman = Alwyn Jones\n| mgrtitle = <!--optional, default: Manager -->\n| manager = Chris Roberts<br>Gafyn Buckland ''(Reserves)''\n| coach = \n| league = [[Cymru North]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 Welsh Alliance League|2018\u201319]]\n| position = [[Welsh Alliance League]]<br>Division 1, 1st (Champions)\n| website = http://www.llangefnifc.co.uk/\n| kit_alt1 = \n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = _bluehoops\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = \n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1 = 0000ff\n| body1 = 0000e6\n| rightarm1 = 0000ff\n| shorts1 = 0000ff\n| socks1 = 0000ff\n| pattern_name1 = Home\n| kit_alt2 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = _redhoops\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = ff0000\n| body2 = e60000\n| rightarm2 = ff0000\n| shorts2 = ff0000\n| socks2 = ff0000\n| pattern_name2 = Away\n| kit_alt3 = \n| pattern_la3 = \n| pattern_b3 = \n| pattern_ra3 = \n| pattern_sh3 = \n| pattern_so3 = \n| leftarm3 = \n| body3 = \n| rightarm3 = \n| shorts3 = \n| socks3 = \n| pattern_name3 = <!--optional, default: Third colours -->\n| current = \n}}\n\n'''Llangefni Town Football Club''' ({{lang-cy|Clwb P\u00eal-droed Tref Llangefni}}) are a Welsh [[football (soccer)|football]] team based in [[Llangefni]] on [[Anglesey]]. They will be playing in the newly formed [[Cymru North]] from the 2019\u201320 season after gaining promotion from winning the Division 1 title in the [[Welsh Alliance League]]. Their [[reserve team]] currently play in the [[Welsh Alliance League|Welsh Alliance]] Reserve League.\n\nLlangefni Town competed for a single season in the [[Welsh Premier League]] in the [[2007\u201308 Welsh Premier League|2007\u201308]] season and are former members of now defunct [[Cymru Alliance]] between 1999 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.llangefnifc.co.uk/history.php|title=Llangefni Town FC \u2013 History}}</ref>\n\n== Stadium ==\n*Isgraig (1897\u20132000)\n* Cae Bob Parry (2000 \u2013 present)\n\nThe club's ground was chosen to host several matches during the [[2019 Inter Games Football Tournament]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.llangefnifc.co.uk/ Club website]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/llangefnitownfc/ Facebook]\n* [http://twitter.com/LlangefniTownFC Twitter]\n\n{{FAW Championship North & Mid}}\n{{Cymru Alliance}}\n{{Welsh Alliance League}}\n{{Welsh Premier League}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Wales]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1897]]\n[[Category:Sport in Anglesey]]\n[[Category:1897 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Llangefni]]\n[[Category:Cymru Premier clubs]]\n[[Category:Cymru Alliance clubs]]\n[[Category:Welsh Alliance League clubs]]\n[[Category:Gwynedd League clubs]]\n[[Category:Cymru North clubs]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:f922:7c01:a1bc:cedb:4d43:2ef", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Llangefni_Town_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Mildred Seydell", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Mildred Seydell\n| image        = Mildred Seydell.jpg\n| caption      = Mildred Seydel at work\n| birth_name   = Mildred Rutherford Wooley\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1889|3|21}}\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1988|2|20|1889|3|21|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_place  = [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]], Georgia, U.S.\n| occupation   = Writer\n| children     = Paul Vasser Seydel<br />John Rutherford Seydel\n| movement     =\n| period       =\n| notableworks =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| spouse = First husband Paul Bernard Seydel,<br>married February 5, 1910\n}}\n\n'''Mildred Seydell''' (born '''Mildred Rutherford Woolley'''; March 21, 1889&nbsp;\u2013 February 20, 1988) was an American pioneering female journalist in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] who broke the gender barrier in newspapers in the state.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"digital\">{{cite web |url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/meta/html/nge/ngen/meta_nge_ngen_m-10012.html?Welcome |title=Mildred Seydell |publisher=Digital Library of Georgia |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> Seydel wrote as a [[syndicated columnist]] and founded the ''Seydell Journal'', a quarterly journal that was the successor to<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10007 |title=Mildred Seydell |work=Georgia Encyclopedia |publisher=courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> ''The Think Tank'' a short-lived biweekly journal of poetry, articles and reviews (1940\u20131947) (with the [[catchphrase]]/[[logo]] ''Drop it into your thoughts and see the best splash in print'').<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-11132 |title=The Think Tank |publisher=Georgia Encyclopedia, courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> She also founded the Mildred Seydell Publishing Company,<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"digital\"/> and was a regular on the lecture circuit.<ref name=\"iowa\">{{cite web|url=http://sdrc.lib.uiowa.edu/traveling-culture/chau1/pdf/seydell/1/brochure.pdf |title=Brochure for ''Chins up'' and lecture series |publisher=[[University of Iowa]] |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSeydell's parents were Vasser Woolley, an attorney and businessman from Atlanta, and Bessie Cobb Rutherford, the daughter of Colonel John Cobb Rutherford, who was also an attorney.<ref name=\"Marshall\"/><ref name=\"Sorley\">{{cite book|last=Sorley|first=Merrow Egerton|title=Lewis of Warner Hall: the history of a family, including the genealogy of descendants in both the male and female lines, biographical sketches of its members, and their descent from other early Virginia families|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yeWgvfDpwbwC|year=1935|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com|isbn=978-0-8063-0831-9|page=463}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nl8oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA183&dq=Williams+Rutherford&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_UskT6j6Hura0QGgnr3KCA&ved=0CFkQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=Williams%20Rutherford&f=false|title=The National Cyclopaedia of American Biography|accessdate=January 28, 2012|year=1899|chapter=Williams Rutherford |publisher=J.T. White|page=183}}</ref> Named after her grandfather's sister [[Mildred Lewis Rutherford]],{{efn-ua|Parenthetically, the great aunt joined the Georgia Association Opposed to [[women's Suffrage]] and she became a \"vocal opponent\" of women's suffrage and the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], and spearheaded the state organization that convinced Georgia voters to make Georgia the first state to reject it.  Nevertheless, it was ratified on August 18, 1920, and it would apply to Georgia notwithstanding its rejection.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Elizabeth Gillespie |last1=McRae |title=Caretakers of Southern Civilization: Georgia Women and the Anti-Suffrage Campaign, 1914-1920 |journal=[[Georgia Historical Quarterly]] |publisher=[[Georgia Historical Society]] |volume=82 |date=Winter 1998 |pages=801\u201328}}</ref>}} Seydell was the elder of two children.<ref name=\"Marshall\"/><ref name=\"Sorley\"/> Her brother Vasser Woolley, Jr., six or seven years younger than her, would follow their father in business.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://seminars.gatech.edu/hg_event/70594 | title = Vasser Woolley Lecture | first = Margaret | last = Murnane | publisher = Georgia Tech | accessdate =January 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.seydel.com/about/history/ | title = History | publisher = The Seydel Companies, Inc. | accessdate =January 28, 2011| date = 2011-01-21 }}</ref> Seydell matriculated from the [[Lucy Cobb Institute]] in [[Athens, Georgia]] before attending [[the Sorbonne]].<ref name=\"Marshall\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-3178|work=[[The New Georgia Encyclopedia]] |title=Mildred Lewis Rutherford (1851-1928) |first1=Anne E. |last1=Marshall |publisher=[[University of Georgia]] |date=January 29, 2010 |accessdate=January 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1922, she began her career as a [[journalist]] with the [[Charleston Gazette]], a [[West Virginia]] [[newspaper]].<ref name=\"Emory\">{{cite web |url=http://findingaids.library.emory.edu/documents/seydell449/ |title=Seydell papers, including extended biography of Mildred Seydell |publisher=Emory University Library |accessdate=January 24, 2012|date=2005-05-23 }}</ref> In 1924 she moved to Atlanta as a [[correspondent]] for that paper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10006 |title=Mildred Seydell multimedia |publisher=Courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> She was affiliated with the ''[[Atlanta Georgian]]'', one of [[William Randolph Hearst]]'s [[Hearst Corporation|string of newspapers]],<ref name=\"Lisby\"/> working there from 1926 until its closing in 1938.<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19880222&id=ZkMsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qs4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5800,2357343 |title=Obituary, Mildred Seydell, Journalist |date=February 22, 1988 |newspaper=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald Journal]] |page=B2 |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSeydell was twice married. Her first marriage which lasted from 1910 to 1944 was to Paul Bernard Seydel, a Belgian chemist/scientist<ref name=\"chemical\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seydel.com/about/history/ |publisher=The Seydel Companies |title=History |accessdate=January 24, 2012|date=2011-01-21 }}</ref> whom she met while studying at the Sorbonne.<ref name=\"Herald\"/> Their children were Paul and John. After Mr. Seydel died from complications of a [[colectomy]],<ref name=\"chemical\"/> she married Max Seydel, her first husband's brother in 1947. For two decades, Belgium was their home, until their return in 1967 to Atlanta.<ref name=\"Lisby\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-2460 |work=[[The New Georgia Encyclopedia]] |title=Mildred Seydell (1889-1988) |first1=Gregory C. |last1=Lisby |publisher=[[Georgia State University]] |date=May 5, 2010 |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald\"/> She adopted his last name with two \"L\"s as her professional/[[pen name]] at the beginning of her journalistic career.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Emory\"/><ref name=\"Herald\"/>\n\nShe reported on the [[Scopes Trial|Scopes Monkey Trial]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/21/obituaries/mildred-seydell-journalist-98.html |title=Obituary: Mildred Seydell; Journalist, 98 |publisher=Associated Press/[[New York Times]] |date=February 21, 1988 |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref> The Scopes trial was her first major story. She interviewed [[Red Grange|Harold E. \"Red\" Grange]], and was pictured doing his [[hand reading]], a technique she used to \"break the ice\" with an interview subject.<ref name=\"digital\"/><ref name=\"red\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10012 |title=Journalist Mildred Seydell does a \"hand reading\" on Harold E. \"Red\" Grange|work=Georgia Encyclopedia |publisher=courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> Seydell employed the stratagem of hand reading in order to increase her readership, asserting her ability to discover the intimate personality characteristics of big names such as U.S. vice president [[Charles G. Dawes]] and film director [[Cecil B. DeMille]].<ref name=\"Lisby\"/> She even claimed to have been able to read the palms of a well known circus gorilla called Sultan (aka \"John Daniel II\").<ref name=\"Lisby\"/>  During the Scopes trial, Seydell was sent a picture of a monkey's hand, and she was photographed comparing the hands of the Bible toting judge [[John T. Raulston]], [[Clarence Darrow]] and [[William Jennings Bryan]] to it. {{efn-ua|Meanwhile, the [[Chicago Tribune]]'s [[editorial cartoonist]] [[Carey Orr]] drew a [http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/scopes/SCO_CA2.HTM cartoon] \"supporting the proposition that 'Man is not related to the monkey... The proposition would get a lot of support if monkeys could vote on it'\". The Tribune was in a fierce circulation war with the Hearst paper, the [[Chicago Herald-Examiner]].<ref name=\"Teel\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=tHgdCLTPn0EC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=Mildred+Seydell+Publishing+Company#v=onepage&q=Seydell&f=false |volume=5 |title=The public press, 1900-1945: the history of American journalism |first1=Leonard Ray |last1=Teel |page=114 |accessdate=January 26, 2012 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group, Praeger Publishers |place=Westport, Connecticut |year=2006  |isbn=978-0-275-98166-2}}</ref>}}\n\nDuring her career, she interviewed [[Italian Prime Minister]] [[Benito Mussolini]] in 1926,<ref name=\"Lisby\"/> [[Risto Ryti]], the [[Finnish President]] and [[Jean Sibelius]] were interviewed by her while she was on tour in [[Finland]] and [[Lapland (Finland)|Lapland]].<ref name=\"iowa\"/> Other notable personages interviewed by her included (in alphabetical order):  Mrs. [[Edvard Bene\u0161]],  [[George Cukor]], [[\u00c8ve Curie]], [[Marion Davies]], and [[Bette Davis]].<ref name=\"Emory\"/>  She was quoted as having once opined that she \"much preferred to set the stage for adventure rather than the table for dinner\".<ref name=\"Herald\"/><ref name=\"Times\"/>  Her interviews appeared in her column, ''Talks with Celebrities'', ([[Hollywood]] celebrities mostly) which was carried in 27 Hearst papers and the [[Universal News Service]].<ref name=\"Herald\"/><ref name=\"Lusby2\">{{cite journal |first1=Gregory C. |last1=Lisby |first2=Linda L. |last2=Harris |title=Georgia Reporters at the Scopes Trial: A Comparison of Newspaper Coverage |journal=Georgia Historical Quarterly |volume=75 |issue=4 |publisher=[[Georgia Historical Society]] |date=Winter 1991 |pages=784\u2013803 |jstor=40582427 }}</ref> Other columns included ''What Would You Do?'' (advice column from 1926 to 1931) renamed as ''Mildred Seydell Says...'' in 1933,<ref name=\"Emory\"/> and ''All in a Day''.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nIn her columns, she detailed the suffering of the unemployed in the 1930s, and offered advice.<ref name=\"Blackwelder\">{{cite journal |title=Quiet Suffering: Atlanta Women in the 1930s |first1=Julia Kirk |last1=Blackwelder |journal=The Georgia Historical Quarterly |volume=61 |number=2 |date=Summer 1977 |pages=112\u2013124 |publisher=Georgia Historical Society\n|jstor=40580362 }}</ref>\n\nSeydell became intertwined with the [[National Woman's Party]] and the struggle for equal rights following the passage of the 19th Amendment. In 1931 and 1932, she was Chairperson of Atlanta and Georgia, respectively. In 1935 she became associate editor of ''[[Equal Rights (journal)|Equal Rights]]'', its national publication.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Emory\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Mildred Seydell and the National Woman's Party: 1931-1945 |first1=Karen Darlene |last1=Anderson |publisher=Georgia State University |year=2000 |page=254}}</ref>\n\nOther women's organizations in which she was active included: the [[League of Women Voters]], the League of American Pen Women (on March 13, 1931, after meeting with its national president, she was one of 15 Charter members of the Atlanta Branch<ref name=\"APW\">{{cite web |url=http://www.atlantapenwomen.org/about-us.htm |title=National Legal of American Pen Women, Atlanta Branch |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref>), the [[National Federation of Press Women]], the [[Pan American League]], the Atlanta [[Women's Chamber of Commerce]]; and the [[Atlanta Woman's Club]]. From 1941-43, Seydell served as President of the Atlanta Federation of Women's Clubs.  Seydell was also active in the [[General Federation of Women's Clubs|Federation of American Women's Club Overseas]] (in Belgium) and the [[Women's club|American Woman's Club of Brussels]].<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nSeydell was an enthusiastic supporter of the [[Tallulah Falls School]],<ref name=\"tallulah\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bufordlanierwomansclub.com/tallulah.htm |title=Tallulah Falls School |publisher=GFWC Buford Lanier Woman's Club d.b.a. Buford Lanier Woman's Club|first1=Carrie, Chairman |last1=Fishback|accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> \"the only school in the United States which is owned and operated by a state federation of women's clubs.\" It was founded in 1909 by the Georgia Federation of Women's Clubs. As Seydell wrote in the Atlanta Georgian, \"The school is called the 'Light in the Mountains' because ignorance is darkness and knowledge is light.\"<ref name=\"tallulah\"/>\n\n[[United States President|President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] is claimed to have said \"am much interested in your articles\".<ref name=\"iowa\"/>\n\nShe was an accomplished traveler, having gone to at least 52 \"far lands during her career .\"<ref name=\"iowa\"/>\n\nIn 1973, she was honored with the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]] by the Belgian government for her cultural exchange contributions between Belgium and the United States.<ref name=\"Emory\"/> It is one of the [[Order (decoration)|orders of knighthood]]; the highest [[Order (decoration)|order]] of [[Belgium]] and named in honor of [[Monarch|King]] [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]].\n\nShe wrote and planned to publish her autobiography ''The Record on the Wall''.<ref name=\"iowa\"/> Apparently, it was not published. The manuscript is at the Emory Library.<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\n==Death and after==\nHer papers and memorabilia are massively collected ({{convert|67.5|ft|m}} linear) at [[Emory University]].<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nA collection of early and rare Belgian poetry and masterpiece books was created by her at the Emory University Library in 1971, in honor of her late husband Paul.<ref name=\"emory collection\">{{cite web |url=http://marbl.library.emory.edu/collection-overview/featured-collections/paul-bernard-and-mildred-wooley-seydel-memorial-collection |title=Paul Bernard and Mildred Wooley Seydel Memorial Collection |publisher=Emory University Library |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> It was a gift of the charitable foundation, organized in 1982, which bears their names.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dpsslegal.com/attorney/john-rutherford-seydel-ii/ |title=John Rutherford Seydel, II|publisher=Davis, Pickren, Seydel & Snead|accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manta.com/c/mm72c7g/paul-b-mildred-seydel- |title=Paul B. Seydel and Mildred Seydell Foundation |publisher=Manta |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a [[Georgia State Capitol]] ceremony on [[Martin Luther King Day]] in 2012, [[List of Governors of Georgia|Georgia Governor]] [[Nathan Deal]] quoted ''Chins Up!'' by Mildred Seydell: \"Great men don't hate. They are too busy with their accomplishments. Hate flourishes in the breasts of those who have time to feel their wrongs. Hate is the weapon of the defeated, love that of the victor. No man ever won by hating, but many have conquered by loving.\"<ref name=\"McKee\">{{cite news |url=http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/11033350/article-Don-McKee--Governor-Deal-s-MLK-Day-message-worth-repeating|title=Don McKee: Governor Deal's MLK Day message worth repeating |publisher=[[Marietta Daily Journal]] |date=January 17, 2011 |first1=Don |last1=McKee |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n*{{cite book |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell |title=Secret Fathers |place=New York |publisher=[[Grosset & Dunlap]] |year=1930}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell |title=Chins Up! |place=New York |publisher=[[Grosset & Dunlap]]|year=1939 |page=}}\n*{{cite book |title=Come Along to Belgium |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell |publisher=T S Denison & Co |date=January 1969 |isbn= 978-0-513-00521-1}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell|title=Poetry profile of Belgium |place=[[Wauthier-Braine, Belgium]] |publisher=Mildred Seydell Pub. Co |year=c. 1967}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Endnotes===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Further reading===\n*{{cite book |title=Mildred Seydell and the National Woman's Party: 1931-1945 |first1=Karen Darlene |last1=Anderson |publisher=Georgia State University |year=2000 |page=254}}\n*{{cite journal |first1=Mary Elizabeth |last1=Holcomb |title=Mildred Seydell: The Road from Southern Belle to Feminist Journalist |type=master's thesis |publisher=Georgia State University |year=1997}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10012 Journalist Mildred Seydell does a \"hand reading\" on [[Red Grange|Harold E. \"Red\" Grange]]] during the Scopes trial, it being her first major story.\n*[https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zvzn Mildred Seydell papers, 1842-1987]\n*[https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/r9tt5 Paul Bernard Seydel memorial collection, circa 1769-1967]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seydell, Mildred}}\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Writers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Clubwomen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Mildred Seydell\n| image        = Mildred Seydell.jpg\n| caption      = Mildred Seydel at work\n| birth_name   = Mildred Rutherford Wooley\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|mf=yes|1889|3|21}}\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1988|2|20|1889|3|21|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_place  = [[Roswell, Georgia|Roswell]], Georgia, U.S.\n| occupation   = Writer\n| children     = Paul Vasser Seydel<br />John Rutherford Seydel\n| movement     =\n| period       =\n| notableworks =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| spouse = First husband Paul Bernard Seydel,<br>married February 5, 1910\n}}\n\n'''Mildred Seydell''' (born '''Mildred Rutherford Woolley'''; March 21, 1889&nbsp;\u2013 February 20, 1988) was an American pioneering female journalist in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] who broke the gender barrier in newspapers in the state.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"digital\">{{cite web |url=http://dlg.galileo.usg.edu/meta/html/nge/ngen/meta_nge_ngen_m-10012.html?Welcome |title=Mildred Seydell |publisher=Digital Library of Georgia |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> Seydel wrote as a [[syndicated columnist]] and founded the ''Seydell Journal'', a quarterly journal that was the successor to<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10007 |title=Mildred Seydell |work=Georgia Encyclopedia |publisher=courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> ''The Think Tank'' a short-lived biweekly journal of poetry, articles and reviews (1940\u20131947) (with the [[catchphrase]]/[[logo]] ''Drop it into your thoughts and see the best splash in print'').<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-11132 |title=The Think Tank |publisher=Georgia Encyclopedia, courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> She also founded the Mildred Seydell Publishing Company,<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"digital\"/> and was a regular on the lecture circuit.<ref name=\"iowa\">{{cite web|url=http://sdrc.lib.uiowa.edu/traveling-culture/chau1/pdf/seydell/1/brochure.pdf |title=Brochure for ''Chins up'' and lecture series |publisher=[[University of Iowa]] |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSeydell's parents were Vasser Woolley, an attorney and businessman from Atlanta, and Bessie Cobb Rutherford, the daughter of Colonel John Cobb Rutherford, who was also an attorney.<ref name=\"Marshall\"/><ref name=\"Sorley\">{{cite book|last=Sorley|first=Merrow Egerton|title=Lewis of Warner Hall: the history of a family, including the genealogy of descendants in both the male and female lines, biographical sketches of its members, and their descent from other early Virginia families|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yeWgvfDpwbwC|year=1935|publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com|isbn=978-0-8063-0831-9|page=463}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nl8oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA183&dq=Williams+Rutherford&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_UskT6j6Hura0QGgnr3KCA&ved=0CFkQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=Williams%20Rutherford&f=false|title=The National Cyclopaedia of American Biography|accessdate=January 28, 2012|year=1899|chapter=Williams Rutherford |publisher=J.T. White|page=183}}</ref> Named after her grandfather's sister [[Mildred Lewis Rutherford]],{{efn-ua|Parenthetically, the great aunt joined the Georgia Association Opposed to [[women's Suffrage]] and she became a \"vocal opponent\" of women's suffrage and the [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], and spearheaded the state organization that convinced Georgia voters to make Georgia the first state to reject it.  Nevertheless, it was ratified on August 18, 1920, and it would apply to Georgia notwithstanding its rejection.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Elizabeth Gillespie |last1=McRae |title=Caretakers of Southern Civilization: Georgia Women and the Anti-Suffrage Campaign, 1914-1920 |journal=[[Georgia Historical Quarterly]] |publisher=[[Georgia Historical Society]] |volume=82 |date=Winter 1998 |pages=801\u201328}}</ref>}} Seydell was the elder of two children.<ref name=\"Marshall\"/><ref name=\"Sorley\"/> Her brother Vasser Woolley, Jr., six or seven years younger than her, would follow their father in business.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://seminars.gatech.edu/hg_event/70594 | title = Vasser Woolley Lecture | first = Margaret | last = Murnane | publisher = Georgia Tech | accessdate =January 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.seydel.com/about/history/ | title = History | publisher = The Seydel Companies, Inc. | accessdate =January 28, 2011| date = 2011-01-21 }}</ref> Seydell matriculated from the [[Lucy Cobb Institute]] in [[Athens, Georgia]] before attending [[the Sorbonne]].<ref name=\"Marshall\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-3178|work=[[The New Georgia Encyclopedia]] |title=Mildred Lewis Rutherford (1851-1928) |first1=Anne E. |last1=Marshall |publisher=[[University of Georgia]] |date=January 29, 2010 |accessdate=January 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1922, she began her career as a [[journalist]] with the [[Charleston Gazette]], a [[West Virginia]] [[newspaper]].<ref name=\"Emory\">{{cite web |url=http://findingaids.library.emory.edu/documents/seydell449/ |title=Seydell papers, including extended biography of Mildred Seydell |publisher=Emory University Library |accessdate=January 24, 2012|date=2005-05-23 }}</ref> In 1924 she moved to Atlanta as a [[correspondent]] for that paper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10006 |title=Mildred Seydell multimedia |publisher=Courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> She was affiliated with the ''[[Atlanta Georgian]]'', one of [[William Randolph Hearst]]'s [[Hearst Corporation|string of newspapers]],<ref name=\"Lisby\"/> working there from 1926 until its closing in 1938.<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19880222&id=ZkMsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qs4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5800,2357343 |title=Obituary, Mildred Seydell, Journalist |date=February 22, 1988 |newspaper=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald Journal]] |page=B2 |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSeydell was twice married. Her first marriage which lasted from 1910 to 1944 was to Paul Bernard Seydel, a Belgian chemist/scientist<ref name=\"chemical\">{{cite web |url=http://www.seydel.com/about/history/ |publisher=The Seydel Companies |title=History |accessdate=January 24, 2012|date=2011-01-21 }}</ref> whom she met while studying at the Sorbonne.<ref name=\"Herald\"/> Their children were Paul and John. After Mr. Seydel died from complications of a [[colectomy]],<ref name=\"chemical\"/> she married Max Seydel, her first husband's brother in 1947. For two decades, Belgium was their home, until their return in 1967 to Atlanta.<ref name=\"Lisby\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-2460 |work=[[The New Georgia Encyclopedia]] |title=Mildred Seydell (1889-1988) |first1=Gregory C. |last1=Lisby |publisher=[[Georgia State University]] |date=May 5, 2010 |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Herald\"/> She adopted his last name with two \"L\"s as her professional/[[pen name]] at the beginning of her journalistic career.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Emory\"/><ref name=\"Herald\"/>\n\nShe reported on the [[Scopes Trial|Scopes Monkey Trial]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/21/obituaries/mildred-seydell-journalist-98.html |title=Obituary: Mildred Seydell; Journalist, 98 |publisher=Associated Press/[[New York Times]] |date=February 21, 1988 |accessdate=January 24, 2012}}</ref> The Scopes trial was her first major story. She interviewed [[Red Grange|Harold E. \"Red\" Grange]], and was pictured doing his [[hand reading]], a technique she used to \"break the ice\" with an interview subject.<ref name=\"digital\"/><ref name=\"red\">{{cite web |url=http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10012 |title=Journalist Mildred Seydell does a \"hand reading\" on Harold E. \"Red\" Grange|work=Georgia Encyclopedia |publisher=courtesy of Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library, Emory University |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> Seydell employed the stratagem of hand reading in order to increase her readership, asserting her ability to discover the intimate personality characteristics of big names such as U.S. vice president [[Charles G. Dawes]] and film director [[Cecil B. DeMille]].<ref name=\"Lisby\"/> She even claimed to have been able to read the palms of a well known circus gorilla called Sultan (aka \"John Daniel II\").<ref name=\"Lisby\"/>  During the Scopes trial, Seydell was sent a picture of a monkey's hand, and she was photographed comparing the hands of the Bible toting judge [[John T. Raulston]], [[Clarence Darrow]] and [[William Jennings Bryan]] to it. {{efn-ua|Meanwhile, the [[Chicago Tribune]]'s [[editorial cartoonist]] [[Carey Orr]] drew a [http://law2.umkc.edu/faculty/projects/ftrials/scopes/SCO_CA2.HTM cartoon] \"supporting the proposition that 'Man is not related to the monkey... The proposition would get a lot of support if monkeys could vote on it'\". The Tribune was in a fierce circulation war with the Hearst paper, the [[Chicago Herald-Examiner]].<ref name=\"Teel\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=tHgdCLTPn0EC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=Mildred+Seydell+Publishing+Company#v=onepage&q=Seydell&f=false |volume=5 |title=The public press, 1900-1945: the history of American journalism |first1=Leonard Ray |last1=Teel |page=114 |accessdate=January 26, 2012 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group, Praeger Publishers |place=Westport, Connecticut |year=2006  |isbn=978-0-275-98166-2}}</ref>}}\n\nDuring her career, she interviewed [[Italian Prime Minister]] [[Benito Mussolini]] in 1926,<ref name=\"Lisby\"/> [[Risto Ryti]], the [[Finnish President]] and [[Jean Sibelius]] were interviewed by her while she was on tour in [[Finland]] and [[Lapland (Finland)|Lapland]].<ref name=\"iowa\"/> Other notable personages interviewed by her included (in alphabetical order):  Mrs. [[Edvard Bene\u0161]],  [[George Cukor]], [[\u00c8ve Curie]], [[Marion Davies]], and [[Bette Davis]].<ref name=\"Emory\"/>  She was quoted as having once opined that she \"much preferred to set the stage for adventure rather than the table for dinner\".<ref name=\"Herald\"/><ref name=\"Times\"/>  Her interviews appeared in her column, ''Talks with Celebrities'', ([[Hollywood]] celebrities mostly) which was carried in 27 Hearst papers and the [[Universal News Service]].<ref name=\"Herald\"/><ref name=\"Lusby2\">{{cite journal |first1=Gregory C. |last1=Lisby |first2=Linda L. |last2=Harris |title=Georgia Reporters at the Scopes Trial: A Comparison of Newspaper Coverage |journal=Georgia Historical Quarterly |volume=75 |issue=4 |publisher=[[Georgia Historical Society]] |date=Winter 1991 |pages=784\u2013803 |jstor=40582427 }}</ref> Other columns included ''What Would You Do?'' (advice column from 1926 to 1931) renamed as ''Mildred Seydell Says...'' in 1933,<ref name=\"Emory\"/> and ''All in a Day''.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nIn her columns, she detailed the suffering of the unemployed in the 1930s, and offered advice.<ref name=\"Blackwelder\">{{cite journal |title=Quiet Suffering: Atlanta Women in the 1930s |first1=Julia Kirk |last1=Blackwelder |journal=The Georgia Historical Quarterly |volume=61 |number=2 |date=Summer 1977 |pages=112\u2013124 |publisher=Georgia Historical Society\n|jstor=40580362 }}</ref>\n\nSeydell became intertwined with the [[National Woman's Party]] and the struggle for equal rights following the passage of the 19th Amendment. In 1931 and 1932, she was Chairperson of Atlanta and Georgia, respectively. In 1935 she became associate editor of ''[[Equal Rights (journal)|Equal Rights]]'', its national publication.<ref name=\"Lisby\"/><ref name=\"Emory\"/><ref>{{cite book |title=Mildred Seydell and the National Woman's Party: 1931-1945 |first1=Karen Darlene |last1=Anderson |publisher=Georgia State University |year=2000 |page=254}}</ref>\n\nOther women's organizations in which she was active included: the [[League of Women Voters]], the League of American Pen Women (on March 13, 1931, after meeting with its national president, she was one of 15 Charter members of the Atlanta Branch<ref name=\"APW\">{{cite web |url=http://www.atlantapenwomen.org/about-us.htm |title=National Legal of American Pen Women, Atlanta Branch |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref>), the [[National Federation of Press Women]], the [[Pan American League]], the Atlanta [[Women's Chamber of Commerce]]; and the [[Atlanta Woman's Club]]. From 1941-43, Seydell served as President of the Atlanta Federation of Women's Clubs.  Seydell was also active in the [[General Federation of Women's Clubs|Federation of American Women's Club Overseas]] (in Belgium) and the [[Women's club|American Woman's Club of Brussels]].<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nSeydell was an enthusiastic supporter of the [[Tallulah Falls School]],<ref name=\"tallulah\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bufordlanierwomansclub.com/tallulah.htm |title=Tallulah Falls School |publisher=GFWC Buford Lanier Woman's Club d.b.a. Buford Lanier Woman's Club|first1=Carrie, Chairman |last1=Fishback|accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> \"the only school in the United States which is owned and operated by a state federation of women's clubs.\" It was founded in 1909 by the Georgia Federation of Women's Clubs. As Seydell wrote in the Atlanta Georgian, \"The school is called the 'Light in the Mountains' because ignorance is darkness and knowledge is light.\"<ref name=\"tallulah\"/>\n\n[[United States President|President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] is claimed to have said \"am much interested in your articles\".<ref name=\"iowa\"/>\n\nShe was an accomplished traveler, having gone to at least 52 \"far lands during her career .\"<ref name=\"iowa\"/>\n\nIn 1973, she was honored with the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]] by the Belgian government for her cultural exchange contributions between Belgium and the United States.<ref name=\"Emory\"/> It is one of the [[Order (decoration)|orders of knighthood]]; the highest [[Order (decoration)|order]] of [[Belgium]] and named in honor of [[Monarch|King]] [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]].\n\nShe wrote and planned to publish her autobiography ''The Record on the Wall''.<ref name=\"iowa\"/> Apparently, it was not published. The manuscript is at the Emory Library.<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\n==Death and after==\nHer papers and memorabilia are massively collected ({{convert|67.5|ft|m}} linear) at [[Emory University]].<ref name=\"Emory\"/>\n\nA collection of early and rare Belgian poetry and masterpiece books was created by her at the Emory University Library in 1971, in honor of her late husband Paul.<ref name=\"emory collection\">{{cite web |url=http://marbl.library.emory.edu/collection-overview/featured-collections/paul-bernard-and-mildred-wooley-seydel-memorial-collection |title=Paul Bernard and Mildred Wooley Seydel Memorial Collection |publisher=Emory University Library |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref> It was a gift of the charitable foundation, organized in 1982, which bears their names.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dpsslegal.com/attorney/john-rutherford-seydel-ii/ |title=John Rutherford Seydel, II|publisher=Davis, Pickren, Seydel & Snead|accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manta.com/c/mm72c7g/paul-b-mildred-seydel- |title=Paul B. Seydel and Mildred Seydell Foundation |publisher=Manta |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a [[Georgia State Capitol]] ceremony on [[Martin Luther King Day]] in 2012, [[List of Governors of Georgia|Georgia Governor]] [[Nathan Deal]] quoted ''Chins Up!'' by Mildred Seydell: \"Great men don't hate. They are too busy with their accomplishments. Hate flourishes in the breasts of those who have time to feel their wrongs. Hate is the weapon of the defeated, love that of the victor. No man ever won by hating, but many have conquered by loving.\"<ref name=\"McKee\">{{cite news |url=http://mdjonline.com/view/full_story/11033350/article-Don-McKee--Governor-Deal-s-MLK-Day-message-worth-repeating|title=Don McKee: Governor Deal's MLK Day message worth repeating |publisher=[[Marietta Daily Journal]] |date=January 17, 2011 |first1=Don |last1=McKee |accessdate=January 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n*{{cite book |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell |title=Secret Fathers |place=New York |publisher=[[Grosset & Dunlap]] |year=1930}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell |title=Chins Up! |place=New York |publisher=[[Grosset & Dunlap]]|year=1939 |page=}}\n*{{cite book |title=Come Along to Belgium |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell |publisher=T S Denison & Co |date=January 1969 |isbn= 978-0-513-00521-1}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Mildred |last1=Seydell|title=Poetry profile of Belgium |place=[[Wauthier-Braine, Belgium]] |publisher=Mildred Seydell Pub. Co |year=c. 1967}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Endnotes===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Further reading===\n*{{cite book |title=Mildred Seydell and the National Woman's Party: 1931-1945 |first1=Karen Darlene |last1=Anderson |publisher=Georgia State University |year=2000 |page=254}}\n*{{cite journal |first1=Mary Elizabeth |last1=Holcomb |title=Mildred Seydell: The Road from Southern Belle to Feminist Journalist |type=master's thesis |publisher=Georgia State University |year=1997}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Multimedia.jsp?id=m-10012 Journalist Mildred Seydell does a \"hand reading\" on [[Red Grange|Harold E. \"Red\" Grange]]] during the Scopes trial, it being her first major story.\n*[https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zvzn Mildred Seydell papers, 1842-1987]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seydell, Mildred}}\n[[Category:American women journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Writers from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Clubwomen]]\n", "name_user": "A.C.Butner", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mildred_Seydell"}
{"title_page": "CEV Challenge Cup", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|Annual European third-tier level volleyball competition}}\n{{See also|CEV Women's Challenge Cup}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n|title=CEV Challenge Cup\n|current_season=2019\u201320 CEV Challenge Cup\n|logo=CEV Challenge Cup.png\n|pixels=220px\n|caption=Challenge Cup\n|sport=Volleyball\n|founded=1980\n|folded=\n|fame=\n|motto =\n|teams=\n|continent=Europe\n|country=[[Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration Europ\u00e9enne de Volleyball|CEV]] members\n|champion = {{flagicon|RUS}} [[VC Belogorie|Belogorie Belgorod]]<br>(1st title)\n|most_champs = {{Bandiera|ITA}} [[Modena Volley]]<br>(5 titles)\n|website= [https://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/competition.aspx?ID=1195&PID=1952 CEV Challenge Cup] \n|singles=\n|ceo =\n|TV=\n}}\nThe '''CEV Challenge Cup''' is an annual European-wide third-tier level competition for men's [[Volleyball]] clubs. It started in the 1980\u201381 season under the name '''CEV Cup'''. In 2007 it was renamed '''CEV Challenge Cup'''.<ref>{{cite web|url =https://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/Competition.aspx?ID=1035&PID=-1 | title =Competition format | website =cev.eu | publisher =CEV | access-date = 15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n* [[#CEV Cup|CEV Cup]] (1980\u201381 to 2006\u20132007)\n* [[#CEV Challenge Cup|CEV Challenge Cup]] (2007\u201308 to present)\n\n==Title holders==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* 1980\u201381 {{flagicon|FRA}} [[AS Cannes Volley-Ball|AS Cannes]]\n* 1981\u201382 {{flagicon|NED}} [[VISADE Voorburg|Star Lift Voorburg]]\n* 1982\u201383 {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Modena Volley|Panini Modena]]\n* 1983\u201384 {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Modena Volley|Panini Modena]]\n* 1984\u201385 {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Modena Volley|Panini Modena]]\n* 1985\u201386 {{flagicon|ITA}} Kutiba Falconara\n* 1986\u201387 {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Volley Gonzaga Milano|Ener-Mix Milano]]\n* 1987\u201388 {{flagicon|URS}} [[VC Avtomobilist Saint Petersburg|Avtomobilist Leningrad]]\n* 1988\u